'''Asiagate''' is the name of the [[match fixing]] scandal that involved players and officials of the [[Zimbabwe national football team]].<ref name="guardian-2012-02-01">{{cite web|last=Smith|first=David|title=Zimbabwe suspends 80 footballers as part of 'Asiagate' match-fixing probe|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/feb/01/zimbabwe-footballers-suspended-asiagate-match-fixing|publisher=Guardian|accessdate=6 March 2012|date=1 February 2012}}</ref> Zimbabwe's national team (sometimes composed of local players) underwent tours of Asia and lost several games which led to suspicions of match fixing.
The conspiracy was reportedly established by Singaporean [[Wilson Raj Perumal]] who was arrested in Finland for attempting to fix Finnish matches.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moyo|first=Roy|title=Asiagate mastermind jailed in Finland|url=http://www.bulawayo24.com/index-id-sports-sc-soccer-byo-5788-article-Asiagate+mastermind+jailed+in+Finland.html|publisher=Bulawayo24.com|accessdate=6 March 2012|date=20 July 2011}}</ref>
In February 2012, ZIFA Chief Executive Jonathan Mashingaidze was kidnapped having been investigating into the match-fixing.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zimbabwe FA boss kidnapped|url=http://www.kickoff.com/news/27284/zimbabwe-fa-boss-jonathan-mashingaidze-kidnapped.php|publisher=Kickoff.com|accessdate=6 March 2012|date=28 February 2012}}</ref>
As of March 2012, 98 Zimbabwean players had been suspended due to an ongoing investigation.<ref>{{cite web|title=ASIAGATE: More players suspended|url=http://www.zimdiaspora.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7746:asiagate-more-players-suspended&catid=38:travel-tips&Itemid=18|publisher=Zim Diaspora|date=14 February 2011|access-date=2012-03-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801214542/http://www.zimdiaspora.com/index.php?option=com_content|archive-date=2012-08-01|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
The Zimbabwean Warriors' national team coach [[Norman Mapeza]] and his assistant Joey Antipas have also been suspended.{{cn|date=December 2013}}
{{ill|Bekhithemba Ndlovu|fr}} was suspended for 10 years.<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201312040435.html Zimbabwe: Ndlovu Dies]</ref>
