{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox military person | name = Hugh Charles Kennard | image = | caption = | birth_date = 24 June 1918 | death_date = 1995 | placeofburial_label = | placeofburial = | birth_place = | death_place = | placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> | nickname = | birth_name = | allegiance = {{Flag icon|UK}} UK | branch = {{air force|UK}} | serviceyears = 1937–1949 | rank = [[Wing Commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] | servicenumber = | unit = [[No. 66 Squadron RAF]] | commands = | battles = World War II *[[Battle of Britain]] | battles_label = | awards = [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] | relations = | laterwork = Civilian aviator }} [[Wing Commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] '''Hugh Charles Kennard''',<ref name="SEE"/> [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]] (24 June 1918 – 1995) was a [[Royal Air Force]] pilot during [[World War II]] and later an [[entrepreneur]] in civil aviation.<ref name="BBM">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbm.org.uk/as-kennard.htm|title=The Airmen's Stories – F/Lt. H C Kennard|publisher=The Battle of Britain London Monument|date=2007|accessdate=6 March 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716094514/http://www.bbm.org.uk/as-kennard.htm|archivedate=16 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==Personal life== Kennard was born on 24 June 1918 at [[Coxheath]], Kent, United Kingdom, the son of Charles W Kennard and his wife.<ref name=Times010718>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Births |day_of_week=Monday |date=1 July 1918 |page_number=1 |issue=41830 |column=A}}</ref> He was educated at [[Cranbrook School, Kent|Cranbrook School]] in [[Kent]].<ref name="BBM"/> Kennard's first wife was Jean Muriel Crossley, they had one son and his second was Audrey,<ref name=Flight141065>{{Cite magazine|title=Air Kruise |magazine=Flight |issue=14 October 1955 |page=628 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1955/1965%20-%201513.html}}</ref> whom he married in November 1940.<ref name=SS90>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jcca.us/Articles/CarWStor/CarWStor.htm |title=A CAR WITH STORIES TO TELL |first=Bob |last=Golfen |publisher=Jaguar Club of Central Arizona |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> Kennard married Jane Neville in 1969 and the couple had another son. He died in 1995.<ref name="BBM"/> Kennard had one son by his first wife, Jeremy, and a further son, Julian by his third wife.
==Career==
===RAF career=== Kennard joined the [[Royal Air Force]] on a short-service commission in January 1938 as an acting [[pilot officer]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34476|supp=y|page=517|date=25 January 1938}}</ref> His commission was confirmed in October 1938.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34566|supp=y|page=6820|date=1 November 1938}}</ref> During 1938, he bought the [[prototype]] [[SS 90|Jaguar SS 90 roadster]], registered [[Vehicle registration plates of the United Kingdom|ARW295]].<ref name=SS90/> He served with [[No. 66 Squadron RAF]] and [[No. 610 Squadron RAF|610 Squadron]] between until 1940. In early 1940, he flew missions over [[Dunkirk]] during the [[evacuation of Dunkirk|evacuation]] and, in mid-1940, was engaged in combat missions over southern England.<ref name="SEE">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesoutheastecho.co.uk/Pilots/Kennard_HC.htm|title=F/Lt. H. C. Kennard|publisher=The South East Echo|accessdate=6 March 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003031403/http://www.thesoutheastecho.co.uk/Pilots/Kennard_HC.htm|archivedate=3 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In July 1940, Kennard was promoted to [[flying officer]]<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34960|supp=y|page=5832|date=4 October 1940}}</ref> and assigned to [[No. 306 Polish Fighter Squadron]] as a flight commander in the [[Hawker Hurricane]] squadron formed by the Polish government at [[RAF Church Fenton]] in Yorkshire. The squadron became active towards the end of the [[Battle of Britain]].<ref name="BBM"/> Kennard sold the SS 90 some time after his marriage in November 1940.<ref name=SS90/>
In 1941, Kennard was promoted to [[flight lieutenant]]<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=36514|supp=y|page=2230|date=12 May 1944}}</ref> and assisted in the formation of [[No. 121 Squadron RAF]], a Hurricane squadron composed of American volunteer pilots, based at [[RAF Kirton in Lindsey]] in [[Lincolnshire]]. The squadron became operational in two months. After converting from Hurricanes to [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s, Kennard led the American squadron on missions across the English Channel. The station commander at the time purchased a five-gallon tin of [[peanut butter]] from [[Harrods]] in order to make the American personnel feel more at home.
After the [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] and the declaration of war by the United States, Kennard is reputed to have proposed a toast with the words "You're all in it now, Yanks!" He was made squadron commander in early 1942 and was shot down and wounded in July while participating in a bomber-escort mission.<ref name="BBM"/> Having flown 58 missions since taking command, he was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] for a combat operation in May 1942 in which he engaged eight enemy aircraft, shooting down two, with a third claimed as probable and a fourth damaged.
Later that month Kennard led his flight in a successful attack on a [[minesweeper (ship)|minesweeper]] and later still attacked and sank an [[naval trawler|armed trawler]] off the Dutch coast.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=35614|supp=y|page=2870|date=26 June 1942}}</ref><ref name=Flight160742>{{Cite magazine|title=Service Aviation |magazine=Flight |issue=16 July 1942 |page=78 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1942/1942%20-%201506.html}}</ref> Kennard relinquished command of the squadron in September 1942.<ref name="BBM"/> In October 1942, Kennard was wounded in action.<ref name=Flight151042>{{Cite magazine|title=Service Aviation |magazine=Flight |issue=15 October 1942 |page=432 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1942/1942%20-%202186.html}}</ref> He was promoted to acting [[squadron leader]] in 1943.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=36092|supp=y|page=3206|date=13 July 1943}}</ref>
===Later career=== After relinquishing command of 121 Squadron, Kennard was assigned to the Directorate of Fighter Operations in the [[Air Ministry]] and then to a role overseeing troop movements. He returned to operations in May 1945, having been confirmed as a squadron leader,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=37074|supp=y|page=2480|date=8 May 1945}}</ref> and took command of a Spitfire squadron – [[No. 74 Squadron RAF]]. He commanded a station until he left the RAF in 1946 and then served with the [[Royal Auxiliary Air Force]] from 1949<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38588|supp=y|page=1938|date=19 April 1949}}</ref> to 1952, commanding [[No. 500 Squadron RAF]] and flying [[Gloster Meteor]]s. He was granted the rank of [[wing Commander (rank)|wing commander]] in April 1949.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38588|supp=y|page=1942|date=19 April 1949}}</ref> He took [[Anthony Eden]], the squadron's [[honorary air commodore]], for a ride in a Meteor.<ref name="BBM"/>
In 1949, Kennard was to have taken part in a Royal Auxiliary Air Force Race based at [[RAF Elmdon]]. He was due to fly a Meteor 3,<ref name=Flight210749>{{Cite magazine|title=The National Air Races |magazine=Flight |issue=21 July 1949 |page=75 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1949/1949%20-%201422.html}}</ref> but the aircraft was unable to participate in the race because of the weather at its base,<ref name=Flight040849>{{Cite magazine|title=The National Air Races |magazine=Flight |issue=21 July 1949 |page=133 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1949/1949%20-%201369.html}}</ref> [[RAF West Malling]].<ref name=Flight310850>{{Cite magazine|title=South Coast Air Race Entries |magazine=Flight |issue=31 August 1950 |page=253 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1950/1950%20-%201645.html}}</ref> He retired from active service and was appointed to the reserve in 1952<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=39539|supp=y|page=2578|date=9 May 1952}}</ref> and relinquished his commission in 1959.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=41636|supp=y|page=1160|date=13 February 1959}}</ref>
===Civilian aviation=== After he left the Royal Air Force, Kennard became an entrepreneur in civilian aviation. He founded or became director of, several airlines and aviation-related companies, including [[Air Kruise]], which ran [[Ramsgate Airport]], and [[Silver City Airways]].<ref name="BBM"/> In 1946, Kennard formed Air Kruise at [[Lympne Airport]]. In August of that year, Kennard took delivery of the first civilian [[Miles Messenger]], G-AHZS, from [[Miles Aircraft|Miles Aircraft Ltd]].{{sfn|Collyer|1992|p=141}} The handover was made at [[Heston Aerodrome]].<ref name=Flight050946>{{Cite magazine|title=Civil Aviation News |magazine=Flight |issue=5 September 1946 |page=251 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1946/1946%20-%201741.html}}</ref> Air Kruise operated [[Airspeed Consul]]s, [[Auster Autocrat]]s, [[Miles Messenger]]s, [[Miles Gemini]]s and [[Percival Proctor]]s.<ref name=Flight280449>{{Cite magazine|title=Air Charter Guide |magazine=Flight |issue=28 April 1949 |page=504 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1949/1949%20-%200765.html}}</ref> They also operated [[de Havilland Dragon Rapide]]s.{{sfn|Collyer|1992|p=143}}
Kennard and his wife came second in the 1946 Folkestone Trophy Air Race, the first to be held at Lympne after the war.<ref name=Flight120946>{{Cite magazine|title=With 'Flight's Camera at Folkestone ...' |magazine=Flight |issue=12 September 1946 |page=285 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1946/1946%20-%201817.html}}</ref> In October 1948, Kennard formed the Kent Coast Flying Club, which was based at Lympne and replaced the Cinque Ports Flying Club, which had folded on 1 October.<ref name=Flight141048>{{Cite magazine|title=Civil Aviation News ... |magazine=Flight |issue=14 October 1948 |page=457 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1948/1948%20-%201713.html}}</ref> Amongst the aircraft operated was [[Miles Magister]] G-AKJX.{{sfn|Collyer|1992|p=117}} In 1953, Air Kruise moved from Lydd to [[Ramsgate Airport|Ramsgate]].{{sfn|Collyer|1992|p=143}} In 1958, Kennard formed Aircraft Engineering and Maintenance Ltd at Ramsgate. The company overhauled aircraft engine gearboxes,{{sfn|Finnis|2006|pp=5–10}} hydraulic systems and instruments. As of 2011, AEM is known as Aviation Engineering & Maintenance Ltd and is a part of [[Rio Tinto Zinc]].<ref name=AEAT>{{Cite journal|title=AEM Offer Comprehensive Repair and Overhaul Service |journal=Aircraft Engineering and Aerospace Technology |volume= 59 |issue= 4 |page=13|url=http://www.emeraldinsight.com/journals.htm?articleid=1683723&show=abstract |doi=10.1108/eb036425}}</ref>
Kennard was joint Managing Director of [[Silver City Airways]] until his resignation in November 1960.<ref name=Flight021260>{{Cite magazine|title=Brevites |magazine=Flight |issue=2 December 1960 |page=892 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1960/1960%20-%202852.html}}</ref> In May 1961, Kennard formed a new airline, which was to be based at [[Rochester Airport (England)|Rochester Airport]].<ref name=Flight180561>{{Cite magazine|title=Kennard Family Airways |magazine=Flight |issue=18 May 1961 |pages=680–81}} ([http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1961/1961%20-%200670.html p680], [http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1961/1961%20-%200671.html p681])</ref> This airline was [[Air Ferry Limited|Air Ferry]]. For operational reasons, [[Manston Airport]] was chosen as the base.<ref name=Flight020862>{{Cite magazine|title=Air Ferry Ltd |magazine=Flight |issue=2 August 1962 |page=158 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1962/1962%20-%201330.html}}</ref> Air Ferry commenced operations on 30 March 1963.<ref name=FI130264>{{Cite magazine|title=Air Commerce... |magazine=Flight International|issue=30 March 1963 |page=236 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1963/1963%20-%200379.html}}</ref>
In November 1964, Kennard formed [[Invicta International Airlines]] at Manston, following a takeover of Air Ferry by Air Holdings Ltd.{{sfn|Finnis|2006|pp=5–10}} Although based at Manston, the head office was at Ramsgate.<ref name=FI150465>{{Cite magazine |title=World Airline Survey... |magazine=Flight International |issue=15 April 1965 |page=586 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1965/1965%20-%202152.html}}</ref> On 3 January 1969, Invicta International was merged with [[British Midland]]. Invicta became "British Midland – Invicta Cargo.{{sfn|Finnis|2006|pp=76–92}}
The merger was forced by London merchant bank Minster Trust. In July, the air cargo operation was sold back to Kennard,<ref name=FI170769>{{Cite magazine|title=Invicta out of BMA consortium |magazine=Flight International|issue=17 July 1969 |page=236 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1969/1969%20-%202436.html}}</ref> who formed a new company, Invicta Airways (1969) Ltd.{{sfn|Finnis|2006|pp=76–92}} In February 1973, European Ferries Group acquired a 76% holding of Invicta.{{sfn|Finnis|2006|pp=133–54}} On 30 September 1975, Invicta ceased operations as a result of European Ferries decision to cease airline operations.{{sfn|Finnis|2006|pp=169–79}}
In February 1976, the assets of Invicta were bought by Universal Air Transport Sales, which Kennard had set up.<ref name=FI140276>{{Cite magazine|title=Invicta Flies Again |magazine=Flight International |issue=14 February 1976 |page=326 |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1976/1976%20-%200236.html}}</ref> Invicta was sold in 1980, Kennard left the company and established a business at [[Canterbury]] restoring classic cars.{{sfn|Finnis|2006|pp=213–20}}
