[[File:Military stress card.jpg|thumb|upright|Front and back of stress card issued by U.S. Navy Fleet and Family Support Center]]
The '''military stress card''', a wallet-size card incorporating a [[liquid crystal thermometer]], is the subject of debate whether or not its use by [[United States Armed Forces]] recruits is an [[urban legend]]. According to [[Snopes.com]] and ''[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]'', stress cards can not be used by recruits in [[Recruit training|boot camp]] to halt training.{{sfn|Mikkelson|2011}}{{sfn|Schogol|2011}} But according to ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine, it was issued for this purpose by the [[United States Navy|Navy]] for recruits heading to boot camp at [[Recruit Training Command, Great Lakes, Illinois|RTC Great Lakes]].{{sfn|Thompson|2001}} Whether urban legend or not, the purported use of them in boot camp is cited as evidence of the softening of U.S. military forces, degrading readiness to fight and even causing [[post-traumatic stress disorder]] in those who are exposed to the psychological rigors of combat.{{sfn|Turpen|2014}}{{sfn|Thompson|2001}}

==Background==
[[File:US military enlisted accessions 1975-2001.png|thumb|upright=1.2|Trends in recruiting 1975-2001 showing total numbers of enlisted recruits in all branches of US armed forces in light blue and percentage of recruiting goals met in dark blue. Percentage of recruits with at least a high school diploma is shown in gold, percentage with an above average [[Armed Services Vocational Aptitude Battery|AFQT]] in orange,{{ref|a|*}} and the percentage called "high quality", with both a diploma and above-average AFQT score, is in purple.{{sfn|Kapp|2002}} ]]
The stress cards were said to have appeared during the [[Clinton administration]] (1993-2001).{{sfn|Mikkelson|2011}} Though all branches of the armed services met or exceeded their recruiting goals through this period, recruit quality fell from the peak reached in 1992. "High quality" enlisted recruits, defined as having both a [[high school diploma]] and an above average [[Armed Services Vocational Aptitude Battery|Armed Forces Qualification Test]] (AFQT) score were far lower in the 1970s, rising through the 1993 establishment of the first minimum requirement for recruit quality, which was met every year since, in spite of dropping in subsequent years.{{ref|a|*}} Possible explanations offered in hindsight were waning public enthusiasm for the military in the years immediately following the successful [[Gulf War]] (1990-1991), which coincided with decreasing unemployment and  better civilian pay relative to the military; more high school graduates attending college instead of enlisting; and a perceived drop in quality of life and job satisfaction in the military. Even at their lowest point in 2000, these statistical measures of recruit quality remained well above those of the 1970s and early to mid 1980s.{{sfn|Kapp|2002}}

==Notes==
* {{note|a}}The population that takes the AFQT is larger than the population that of those who subsequently enlist, allowing for a large majority of enlistees to be above average, compared to population including both enlistees and non-enlistees.

